Tollefson April 2021

1 Intro outline

Framing: Urban environmental health hazards are generally imagined as radiating outward from industrial urban cores. Rural environmental health risks are topologically about the same: imagined as radiating from a limited class of industrial point-sources (mines, etc). In both cases, spatial exposure depends on proximity to discrete point sources of pollution, whether that is residential proximity or proximity as a function of workplace hazards - from Pellow’s (2004) work on recycling industries to the significant body of research tracking farmworker exposure to agricultural toxicants (Quandt et al., 2006; Saville & Adams, 2021; Soper, 2021).

This is also the case where environmental risk is incorporated into research on urban development and change: Where suburbanization literature deals with (built) environments, environmental risk is a factor that pushes white and affluent residents out of city centers. A concurrent literature tracks the social benefits of living in this kind of suburb: in short, access to health and wealth. Neighborhoods in this way afford a set of spatial resources that have benefits and consequences for those who live there - benefits that accumulate in part because this kind of residential mobility is relatively “sticky” (DeLuca & Rosenbaum, 2003).

But it matters where that urban expansion happens. In many regions, outer suburbs and satellite cities are ringed by intensive and extensive agricultural land, a form of industrial land use that produces a particular kind of chemical environment composed of accumulated and continually-reapplied pesticides and herbicides. As suburbs grow and change, the social dimensions of pesticide adjacency and exposure change as well. At the same time, urban expansion leads to the conversion of industrial agricultural land into residential housing tracts - and produces, accordingly, new landscapes of adjacency and exposure.

What happens when cities expand in this way? When suburbs expand, who moves to suburbs with high levels of pesticide contamination? In what ways do new forms of suburban expansion replicate patterns of environmental inequality?

Using longitudinal data on pesticide application, urban change, and new residential construction in the Central Valley in California, I’ll make two interrelated arguments:

  1. suburbs are linked to rural regions through a set of inequitably-distributed chemical relations: understanding suburbanization requires a shift from an urban-centered EJ frame to once that accounts for rural land use socioenvironmental succession (or something like that!)
  2. suburbs are a site for the reproduction of environmental inequalities most often observed in industrial urban cores, as conditioned on point 1, above

I focus on California as CA maintains an exceptionally detailed pesticide registration system, with chemical-specific application data going back to the mid-1970s.

2 Lit: Environmental inequality and (sub)urban transformation

Since at least the emergence of the modern industrial city, and accelerating with rise of the environmental justice movement in the 1980s, inhabited land has been understood to carry a level of environmental risk; that risk, like other goods and resources, is distributed unequally. Establishing environmental inequality as a political reality and a field of scholarship relied on an accumulation of spatial research social-environmental research that linked residential segregation and toxic siting (Arora & Cason, 1999; Crowder & Downey, 2010; L. Downey, 2006; Manduca & Sampson, 2019; Mohai et al., 2009). Substantial work has documented how low-income, indigenous, and minority communities disproportionately bear the environmental risks and health impacts associated with industrial production and waste, and hazardous facility siting remains a central organizing issue for environmental justice research and social movements (Agyeman et al., 2016; Bullard et al., 2000; David N. Pellow, 2017). As a result, environmental inequality is increasingly recognized as a central organizing concept for understanding the development of contemporary cities.

Driven by in-depth analysis of contemporary and near-historical cases, environmental inequality research has imagined site contamination as an inert background for the arrangement of social groups in urban contexts. Meso-level risk mechanisms vary, ranging from inequalities in housing choice and mobility that concentrate minority and low-income population in already-polluted neighborhoods, to mechanisms that bring new sources of pollution to poor city sectors (Pellow’s “perpetrator-victim scenario”). Existing hazards “push” wealthy and mobile residents away from polluted neighborhoods, while the presence of white and wealthy residents likewise “push” sources of environmental pollution away from their neighborhoods of residence (Crowder & Downey, 2010; Liam Downey, 2005). Neighborhood sorting, here, emerges as a rational response to a dialectic of access and exposure: Inequalities in exposure to urban environmental hazards combine with a lack of access to employment, safe and affordable housing, and other resources, contributing to the reproduction of urban inequality and racial-spatial-economic segregation. This model of neighborhood change and residential outcomes is perhaps the most enduring legacy of early Chicago School human ecologists (Hawley, 1986). Recent longitudinal research has complicated this picture by introducing a model of joint land use and residential churning, in which residential outcomes are the result of two mechanisms of neighborhood change: Those of migration and residential sorting on the one hand, and parcel-level turnover in residential and industrial land use on the other (Frickel & Elliott, 2018; Marlow et al., 2020).

Explanations of early suburbanization generally treat residential and industrial churning as a pair of separate - if interrelated - social processes, in which city spaces are primarily shaped by residential sorting processes. Turnover in the built environent alternately serves as an explanatory tool for individual-level residential choices or, in the gentrification and neighborhood change literature, an outcome of neighhood-level demographic change. Under this framework, early suburbs were populated by white working- and middle-class families who were repulsed by the environmental pollutants of industrial urban cores and attracted to a vision of safety and racial homogeneity offered by new suburban development - aided by a postwar boom in highway construction, exurban greenfield development, and new forms of systematized mortgage lending (Mieszkowski & Mills, 1993). Early development thus represented a new frontier for the racialized concentration of wealth across generations, the suburbs a horizontal extension of existing patterns of urban transformation and competition for resources (though, of course, intergenerational transfer is one factor among many that contribute to contemporary inequalities - see Conley, 2001).

This form of urban expansion broadly continued through at least through the 1980s. In the intervening decades, as increasing access to car ownership began to undermine the privileged access to speedy transportation enjoyed by early suburban residents, “white flight” began to reverse (LeRoy & Sonstelie, 1983) - and as wealth returned to urban centers, poor city residents were increasingly pushed outward into the original inner suburbs (Hannigan & Richards, 2017). The “suburbanization of poverty” is a global phenomenon, shaped at once by the increasing mobility of capital and the growth of precarious employment [Van der Waal (2010); citation?]. Where early suburbanization might be understood as an exercise in extraction, in which the employment and infrastructure resources of urban employment centers were transferred to new suburbs and wealthy exurbs, contemporary patterns of suburbanization add a counterveiling process of agglomeration: Global capital accumulates in urban centers and outer suburbs, with the poor stranded in the “in-between cities” of the old inner suburbs (Hannigan & Richards, 2017) in a structure resembling a “donut” (Hannigan & Richards, 2017). In recent decades, even as the number of poor suburban residents has increased, the income composition of individual suburban neighborhoods has remained relatively stable (Schouten, 2020). Suburbs remain highly segregated (Massey & Tannen, 2018) - and increasing component of which is accounted for by growing differences between metropolitan regions (Lichter et al., 2015) - with strong significant effects observed by race independent of income (Logan, 2014). Indeed, sprawl has been shown to aggravate multiple forms of inequality throughout periods of suburban migration (see Bullard et al., 2000).

2.1 Suburbanization as ‘land change’ and socioeconomic-environmental succession

The suburb is therefore a spatial construct and a spatial outcome, and early models of suburban development naturally sought to account for its distinct spatial features - features wrought, necessarily, through the transformation of exurban land, as suburban development remade periurban fields, farms, and forests into low-density housing and sprawling transportation infrastructure. But much like the new suburban residents themselves, researchers concerned with suburban transformation remained focused on the urban core: Suburbs were incorporated into the sociological imagination as an urban phenomenon, as an outcome or a driver of processes of urban development and neighborhood change. Much suburban environmental research, accordingly, has focused on the role of suburbanization in shifting the environmental impact of cities writ large. Suburbs are understood to produce a greater environmental burden than denser forms of residential organization: suburban residents consume more resources (cite) and produce a higher environmental burden(?) than their center-city neighbors. Globally, suburbanization is estimated to account for an X% increase in greenhouse gas emissions over X years. Others have addressed the environmental burden of suburban sprawl as a land-based phenomenon, tracking the local environmental cost of transforming forest to sprawl - though environmental-sociological studies of suburban land transformation remain relatively few (Rudel, 2009, more citations). In other words, while recent urban environmental inequality research has integrated environmental impact and exposure through a joint analysis of residential churning and iterative turnover in industrial forms of land use, research on suburban-environmental relationships remain focused on exogenous environmental impacts, which are understood to be the outcome of endogenous processes of changes to urban development patterns. Suburban migration is understood in part as a result of the desire of urban residents to escape neighborhoods that are at once “punishing and toxic” (Manduca & Sampson, 2019); suburban development, in turn, leads to increased global environmental harm, either through increases in per-capita consumption of resources or through the direct or indirect loss of natural areas (cf. Rudel, 2009).

Two distinct features of urban and suburban development trouble this “global” suburban-environmental focus. First, suburban development is not only a process of converting “unimproved” land to housing, because exurban land is rarely “natural.” Rather, to generalize from early models of urban development, many cities are ringed in part by developed, profitable land, from intensive agricultural use in nearby regions to extensive (commodity?) farming in the rural hinterlands (Mieszkowski & Mills, 1993). Much like urban industrial churning is a process of industrial turnover (cf. Frickel & Elliott, 2018), the prevalence of the farmland-to-suburb conversion means that many suburban tracts play host to multiple iterations of developed and industrialized landscapes, overlapping in space if not in time. Suburban spaces thus contain a diversity of local environmental relations depending on “what came before”: Suburban residents reside in regions with histories of human impact on the land equally as extensive (if not as intensive) as many urban zones.

Indeed, the first residents of mid-20th century auto-dependent suburban expansions moved into a landscape that was as much the product of scientific-technical management as the industrial and semi-industrial urban areas they had left behind. Human agriculture has always been a project of large-scale landscape transformation, but the spatial and temporal scale of that impact has been hardly uniform. The emergence of chemical pesticides and herbicides in (DATE), alongside new state-sponsored techniques for rational land management, made possible the precise alteration of ecologies and environments from the molecular to the landscape scale. The technologies and techniques of modern agriculture have additionally both accelerated the conversion of land for efficient, productive agricultural use and slowed the processes by which land again begins to resemble non-agricultural ecosystems: Contemporary agricultural technologies are both more effective and more environmentally persistent than their pre-modern counterparts. 3 Methodology

In 2013, addressing urban scholars, Alan Mace argued for an integrative approach to the suburb as a spatial phenomenon: “we need to hold on to the role of the suburb not as apart from the city but as part of a wider urban canvas and the changes happening across it” (13). In this paper, I apply Mace’s provocation to the suburbs: First by understanding suburban development as a process of local socioenvironmental succession that replaces one form of profitable land development with another, and, second, by integrating iterative change to suburban land use alongside an analysis of ongoing suburban residential churning. I develop my analysis inductively: I first outline a method to identify regions where agricultural land is “turning over” into suburban housing. These regions form the backbone a parcel-level analysis of suburban land transformation, backed by detailed crop-specific land use data and recent tract-level demographic measures.

3.1 Data

While much of the (sub)urbanization literature has focused on demographic and economic drivers of urban and suburban development, I primarily take advantage of public land use and population datasets maintained by state and federal agencies, including remote sensing data. Aerial and remote sensing data provide a “freeze frame” view of the spatial patterns associated with urban change and allow for a comprehensive longitudinal analysis of land cover and land use at a broad spatial scale (Dietzel et al., 2005). I join remote sensing information with agricultural data maintained by the California Department of Pesticide Regulation, which aggregates pesticide data by public land survey system (PLS) sections, each approximately one mile. PLS section-wise data and aerial imagery are standard data sources for land and resource governance and have found broad application in the geographic literature, though they remain relatively under-exploited by social scientists (Dugoua et al., 2018). This paper integrates geographic data with traditional social-scientific measures at both the county and census tract level. Data sources are outlined in Table 3.1 below.

3.2 Spatial measures of farm-to-suburb conversion

This paper begins with a statewide analysis of landscape change at the county level, drawing on two non-spatial measures. The first measure is drawn from the US Agricultural Census, a highly detailed survey of US farmland, farm economies, and farmers, available in five-year increments starting in 1997. Agricultural Census data are used to measure the reduction in active farm acreage by county between 1997 and 2017. Second, I measure the total number of new residential building permits per capita across the same period to produce an estimate of county-level residential construction. This second measure is based on annual US Building Permits Survey data, scaled according to annual ACS population estimates. I integrate each of these measures using a Getis-Ord Gi-star hot-spot analysis to produce a measure of contiguous counties that represent local maxima in the conversation of farmland to new housing. Growing agricultural pesticide risk related to suburban expansion may be intuitively expected in regions where farmland conversion and new residential construction are overlapping or adjacent.

3.3 Understanding farmland conversion at the local level

I draw on two additional sources of data to understand what that transformation looks like at the local level: Who is moving the new, formerly-agricultural housing tracts? And what kinds of agricultural toxicants might we expect to find there? To answer these questions, it is necessary to analyze pesticide application at a fine spatial scale. This requires generating an estimate of the point sources of agricultural pollution.

To map chemical exposure, I draw on agricultural pesticide data from California’s Pesticide Use Reporting (PUR) system, which lists the total pounds of each registered pesticide or fertilizer applied within each one-mile-square PLS section on an annual basis. County- and region-level environmental health researchers generally calculate exposure by evenly apportioning PUR section-wise data within intersectional regional geographies (see, for example, Huang & London, 2012; Larsen et al., 2017). The social-spatial dynamics of suburban expansion, however, play out at the scale of neighborhoods and individual housing parcels: a much finer geography than a county or even a single census tract.

Interpolating PUR data requires some abstraction. Following Larsen et al (Larsen et al., 2017), I first select CA pesticide data according to EPA toxicity ratings, producing a measure of the total application of highly-toxic agricultural pesticides by PLS section. Twenty years of pesticide application data are aggregated by PLS section to produce a measure of the total pesticide burden for each square-mile region from 1997 to 2017. That total figure is then distributed proportionally across each of the 30-meter agricultural plots identified under the NLCD agricultural land use categories. Assigning section-level pesticide data to smaller NLCD-derived geographies partially controls for the high degree of land-use variation within PLS sections, especially on the fringes of urban areas where there are often stark physical boundaries between agricultural and non-agricultural land. While this approach does not account for differences in pesticide application across agricultural plots within a single PLS section, it provides an approximation of the likeliest point-sources for potential pesticide exposure - especially given the average farming operation in Central Valley counties covers a X-acres and is likely to span multiple 30-meter cells.

3.5 New housing construction

While tract-level measures effectively measure the movement of individuals and populations, tract data are not able to capture the physicality of urban expansion and land change: the material transformation of farmland into houses, yards, driveways, and kitchen gardens. We need to zoom in to individual residences - but to do so, we need to find the location of new housing parcels and new residential construction.

Geospatial data on new housing parcels is constructed as follows. For each of the metropolitan regions identified in the sections above, local parcel data are combined with bimonthly building permit tables scraped from local government websites. This produces a spatial dataset of all property parcels that had at least one new residential building constructed since 2012, the earliest year for which all cities provide building permit information.

Most environmental risk assessment in urban contexts deal with aggregate population data and point-sources of pollution; this analysis, however, addresses residential point-locations (that is, new residential parcels) alongside aggregate pollution data. Accordingly, I measure hazard proximity by inverting the standard approach to environmental risk analysis, drawing on distance-based methods (cf. Mohai & Saha, 2015) to approximate levels of potential exposure for each parcel site. Risk associated with residential proximity is measured by selecting all 30-meter point-source cells within 500(?) meters of the boundaries of each new residential parcel - a middle-range distance for primary drift from ground and aerial applications (Ward et al., 2006).

4 Farmland conversion and urban expansion: 1990 to 2017

Drawing on remote-sensing and other spatial data on urban areas in California’s Central Valley, Dietzel et al (2005) proposed a two-step model for the spatial dynamics of (sub)urban expansion development. In their model, historic urban cores and peripheral sub-areas expand outward while remaining spatially and socially distinct; this is followed by a period in which the patchwork of urban agglomerations “coalesce” to form a broader, more uniform urban fabric. Together, the oscillatory cycles between “diffusion” and “coalescence” steadily develop peripheral and intra-urban land to support the housing and infrastructure demands of expanding urban regions. While these patterns may not apply to cities where population growth is managed through intensive redevelopment and densification, spatial expansion models are largely applicable to urban areas in regions with broad expanses of greenfield and agricultural land, as in much of the western US. Indeed, recent urban development patterns continue to generally follow the Alonso-Muth-Mills urban growth model, in which the dialectic of spatial expansion and densification responds to a distance-based gradient of housing cost and desirability (Paulsen, 2012). In central California, home of strong historic preservation and anti-densification development policies and ample exurban, developable land, spatial expansion generally outweighs densification (citation).

I rely on two datasets to measure the spatial structure of urban expansion and farmland conversion at the county level. Urban expansion is measured by the total number of new residential building permits authorized between 1997 and 2017; each year of building permit data is scaled according to that year’s county-wide population estimate. Farm conversion is measured by the change in the number of total acres in active agricultural production over the same period, scaled according to total land area. I avoid proportional measures of farmland conversion because I am interested in the spatial extent of former farm acreage: A significant percent-wise decrease in farmland in a county with minimal agricultural production is not a meaningful measure of large-scale landscape change.

Together, these two measured allow us to identify counties with a large amount of new residential construction as well as a significant loss in farm acreage. To scale upward from county-wide to regional measures, I calculate the Getis-Ord Gi-star statistic for each county in both datasets. The Gi-star statistic produces an estimate of the difference between counties and their immediate neighbors, taking into account the spatial structure of the underlying data. This allows us to identify contiguous regions that represent local maxima for the urban development and farmland variables calculated above.

Figure 4.1: Getis-Ord G* statistics. Left panel: Loss in total farmland, scaled to total county size, 1997 to 2017. Right panel: Total building permits, scaled to county-wide population, 1997 to 2017.

Figure 4.1 displays the output of the Gi-star calculation. The Gi-star statistic follows a standard Z-distribution: Counties greater than 1.65 on the Gi-star measure have urban expansion or farmland conversion results that are significantly higher than their neighbors at the (P < 0.05) level, while counties less than -1.65 on the Gi-star measures are significantly lower. Two patterns stand out above. First, we can identify a large contiguous region of new residential construction in the northern half of the Central Valley. While Sacramento and Yuba Counties, outlined in black, have experienced a large influx of new residents, building permit data doesn’t directly follow recent trends in population growth, which has additionally clustered around the San Francisco Bay Area and in the outlying counties surrounding Los Angeles. Agricultural land loss, meanwhile, is more spatially distributed, with several hot-spots along the south-central coast and in San Joaquin and Kings Counties in the mid-reaches of the Central Valley.

The Central Valley region is also easily identified by mapping agricultural pesticide application. See Figure 4.2, which displays the intensity of 27 years of pesticide application data for each California county, measured by total county land-area, as well as a similar measure of change in yearly pesticide totals between 1990 and 2017. Here, Central Valley counties - notably San Joaquin, the source for Larsen et al’s (2017) pesticide health data - are joined by the wine-growing regions immediately north of the San Francisco Bay area. EPA toxicity categories 3 and 4 are extracted from the full set of EPA-registered chemicals and displayed on the right-hand panel. The lower half displays the proportional change in pesticide application rates over the 27-year span of available data. Agricultural pesticide use has also generally increased over the last thirty years: Central Valley counties applied between 0.5 and 1.3 additional pounds of active ingredient per 1,000 acres of land-area in 2017 compared to 1990. In Tulare County, for instance, an 0.8 pounds-per-thousand-acres increase translated to a 10-fold increase in category 3 and 4 application rates over that period.

Figure 4.2: EPA-registered pesticide application. Left panels display all EPA toxicity levels. Right panels display EPA toxicity codes 3 and 4 only. Upper panels display total application in pounds of active igredient per 1000 acres. Lower panels display the difference in pounds of active ingredient applied per 1000 acres between 1990 and 2017. San Francisco County is an outlier at 94 pounds per thousand acres, total 1990-2017, due to its small land area and high volume of landscaping applications.

8.1 Further research

As Figure 4.2 indicated, California’s Central Valley stands out for its heavy pesticide application, high rate of new residential construction, and, less uniformly, reduction in agricultural land acreage. But the Central Valley is alone: Other agricultural regions experience similar patterns in agricultural land transformation and new building construction, as 8.1 shows, below. While few states monitor pesticide application at the same level of detail as in California, other local hot-spots for farmland conversion and new residential construction - including central Florida, parts of the upper Midwest, and, notably, the Atlanta and Savannah metropolitan areas, may prove fruitful grounds for similar suburban hazard research.
